[[File:Logger Boots.jpg|thumb]]'''Caulk boots''' or '''calk boots''' <ref>[https://www.osha.gov/pls/oshaweb/owadisp.show_document?p_table=FEDERAL_REGISTER&p_id=13496 "Logging Operations"], OSHA</ref> (also called '''cork boots''', '''timber boots''', '''logger boots''', '''logging boots''', or '''corks''')<ref>[http://www.stanhopemuseum.on.ca/kiosk_tools.php "Caulk Boots"], Stanhope Heritage</ref> are a form of rugged footwear, most often associated with the timber trade but also suitable for use in hiking and in other heavy industry such as manufacturing and construction, due to their safety features.<ref name=hix> {{Cite web|url=https://www.hixmagazine.com/types-and-features-of-safety-work-boots/ |last=|first=|date=|title= Work Wear- A Guide For Finding The Best Work Boots For Loggers |archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref>
Timber boots are typically made of leather or suede uppers extending over the ankle, with a thick rubber sole to provide protection and grip, and bearing deep treads or spikes. The ankle is typically cuffed with padded leather. <ref name=hix /><ref> {{Cite web|url=https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=timber+boot|title=Google Images search for Timber boot|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Images|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Timberland 6 inch boots.jpg|thumb|right| [[The Timberland Company]] is a well known manufacturer of timber boots.]]
